                  <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t17700425-46-off296 t17700425-46-cd297"></join>. ++</p>
               <p>W. Webster. I belong to the <placeName id="t17700425-46-crimeloc298">Minerva; she lay at Gun Dock</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t17700425-46-crimeloc298" type="placeName" value="Minerva; she lay at Gun Dock"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t17700425-46-crimeloc298" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t17700425-46-off296 t17700425-46-crimeloc298"></join>. The prisoner Taffe was hired by my mate; she was robbed of the things laid in the indictment, (mentioning them, and the respective owners.) There was nobody on board at the time but a boy, who told me, Taffe came on board at the time; upon which I took him up in Wapping. He confessed, he had robbed the ship; the telescope and a stocking were found in his pocket. He said, he had sold the rest of the things in the city.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17700425-46-person582">
                  Alex.
                   Lindsey
               <interp inst="t17700425-46-person582" type="surname" value="Lindsey"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17700425-46-person582" type="given" value="Alex."></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17700425-46-person582" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I heard Taffe confess he had robbed the ship; and I found a stocking of Thomas Ward's upon him.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17700425-46-person583">
                  Thomas
                   Ward
               <interp inst="t17700425-46-person583" type="surname" value="Ward"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17700425-46-person583" type="given" value="Thomas"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17700425-46-person583" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I saw Taffe after he was taken up. I saw the coat and breeches after they were found, where they were pawned. Spencer said, he knew where they were pawned.</p>
               <p>Taffe's Defence.</p>
               <p>I found these things between four and five o'clock, on board a ship. I was in liquor, and did not know what I said.</p>
               <p>Spencer's Defence.</p>
               <p>I know no more of the robbery than the child unborn. I never was on board that ship; neither do I know where she lay.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17700425-46-person584">
                  Jos.
                   Mildread
               <interp inst="t17700425-46-person584" type="surname" value="Mildread"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17700425-46-person584" type="given" value="Jos."></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17700425-46-person584" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . Spencer has been with me ever since the year 1764; he has been trusted with large sums of money. I always had confidence in him, and thought he deserved it. I had an excellent character with him. He left me in July last. He had a dispute with my maidservant, whom I find he has married since. I never heard any thing ill of him in my life.</p>
               <p>Taffe <rs id="t17700425-46-verdict299" type="verdictDescription">
